    "data": {
        "baby_size_article": {
            "id": "c64e9935-e5c0-49ab-b17a-862856fc9ad3",
            "title": "Week 1 of Pregnancy: What's Happening in Your Body?",
            "overview": "Congratulations! While you might not even know it yet, week 1 of pregnancy marks the beginning of an incredible journey. This week is a bit of a technicality, as it's calculated from the first day of your last menstrual period (LMP). So, technically, you're not *actually* pregnant yet! Let's explore what's going on in your body during this pre-pregnancy phase.",
            "module": "baby_size_approx",
            "template_id": null,
            "content": [
                "Week 1: The Starting Line",
                "It might sound strange, but pregnancy is counted from the first day of your last period. This is because it's difficult to pinpoint the exact moment of conception. By using your LMP, doctors and midwives have a reliable starting point to track your pregnancy.",
                "What's Really Happening?",
                "Your Period: You're having your period! This is the shedding of the uterine lining that occurs when an egg isn't fertilized.\n   Hormonal Shifts: Your body is releasing hormones like estrogen and progesterone, which are essential for regulating your menstrual cycle.\n   Egg Maturation: Inside your ovaries, follicles are developing, each containing an egg. One of these follicles will become dominant and release a mature egg during ovulation.",
                "Preparing for Conception (Even if You're Not Trying Yet!)",
                "Even if pregnancy wasn't planned, or you're actively trying, week 1 is a great time to focus on overall health. Here's how:",
                "Start Taking Folic Acid: Folic acid is crucial for preventing neural tube defects in the developing baby. Aim for at least 400 micrograms daily.\n   Eat a Healthy Diet: Focus on fruits, vegetables, lean protein, and whole grains. A balanced diet provides essential nutrients for both you and a potential baby.\n   Avoid Harmful Substances: Limit or eliminate alcohol, smoking, and recreational drugs. These can negatively impact fertility and early pregnancy.\n   Talk to Your Doctor: If you have any underlying health conditions or are taking medications, consult your doctor. They can advise you on any necessary adjustments.",
                "Common Questions & Concerns",
                "\"I'm not pregnant yet, why is this important?\" Understanding your cycle and taking care of your health now sets the stage for a healthy pregnancy later.\n   \"When will I ovulate?\" Ovulation typically occurs around two weeks after the first day of your LMP. Tracking your cycle can help you pinpoint your fertile window.\n   \"I'm experiencing PMS symptoms, is that normal?\" Yes, PMS symptoms like bloating, mood swings, and breast tenderness are common during your period.",
                "Looking Ahead",
                "Week 1 is the calm before the storm (or rather, the incredible journey!). As you move into week 2, ovulation will occur, and the possibility of conception becomes a reality. Focus on taking care of yourself, learning about your body, and preparing for the exciting weeks to come!",
                "Remember, every woman's experience is unique. Don't hesitate to reach out to your doctor or midwife with any questions or concerns you may have."
            ],
